Intuition
The N-Queens problem requires placing N queens on an N×N chessboard such that no two queens attack each other. This means that:

No two queens can be in the same row.
No two queens can be in the same column.
No two queens can be on the same diagonal.
Since each queen must occupy a different column, we can iterate over columns and attempt to place a queen in a valid row while using backtracking to explore all possible board configurations.

Approach
The algorithm follows a backtracking approach:

Initialize Board

We create an empty board of size N×N filled with '.' using empty_board().
Recursive Backtracking Function (solve_board())

It places queens column by column (iteration variable tracks the column index).
If all columns are filled, we add the board configuration to possibilities.
Check Validity of Queen Placement (can_put())

Ensures no other queen exists in the same row.
Ensures no other queen exists in the upper-left diagonal.
Ensures no other queen exists in the lower-left diagonal.
Backtracking

Try placing a queen in a row.
If a valid placement is found, recurse to place the next queen.
If a placement leads to failure, undo the move (board[row][column] = '.') and try the next row.
Complexity
Time complexity: O(n^n)
In the worst case, at each column, we try all n rows, leading to n^n recursive calls.

Space complexity: O(n^n)
Recursive stack space: O(n) (one call per column).
Board storage: 𝑂(𝑛^2)
Solution storage: O(1)

